Cluster: Politics

title: The 90% Trap: Do Prediction Markets Become Overconfident At Extreme Probabilities?

---

Assumption Being Challenged

Prediction market probabilities are well-calibrated across the entire probability spectrum.

Most users implicitly believe:

If a market is trading at 90%, it should resolve YES roughly 90% of the time.

---

Hypothesis

Prediction markets are reasonably calibrated overall but become systematically overconfident at extreme probability levels (80–99%).

In other words:

High-confidence predictions fail more often than traders expect.


---

Why Readers Care

This matters because:
- Traders rely heavily on probability levels when entering positions.
- Journalists quote market probabilities as confidence estimates.
- Researchers frequently cite prediction markets as calibration benchmarks.
- A 95% probability sounds extremely reliable.

If 95% markets only resolve correctly 88–90% of the time, that changes how people should interpret market prices.

Readers immediately understand the question:

"Can I trust a 90% prediction market?"


---

Suggested Analytical Methods

Calibration Curves

Compare:

Predicted probability 
vs
Actual resolution frequency

---

Brier Score By Probability Bucket

Measure prediction quality across confidence levels.

Determine whether:
- low-confidence markets
- medium-confidence markets
- high-confidence markets

produce different error profiles.

---

Reliability Diagrams

One of the most visually compelling charts available.

Shows:

Expected Probability

vs

Observed Probability

Readers instantly understand it.

---

Confidence Error Distribution

Measure:

Market Probability - Outcome

across all resolved markets.

Identify whether:

- overconfidence dominates
- underconfidence dominates

---

Temporal Calibration

Compare calibration:

- 30 days before resolution
- 14 days before resolution
- 7 days before resolution
- 1 day before resolution

Possible surprise:

Markets may become less calibrated as certainty appears to increase.

---

Market Category Comparison

Compare:

- Elections
- Nominations
- Congress
- Geopolitics

Potential finding:

Some domains may be calibrated while others are wildly overconfident.



